{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/projecting-and-visualizing-infrastructure-growth-trends-with-python-1e578d9e4260", "time": 1683004070.8126988, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/projecting-and-visualizing-infrastructure-growth-trends-with-python-1e578d9e4260/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Visualizing Infrastructure Growth with Python and Tableau | by Vajiha Sipra | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Visualizing Infrastructure Growth with Python and Tableau", "description": "How Python can provide solutions to your storage questions"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/vajiha-sipra-83842224/", "anchor_text": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/vajiha-sipra-83842224/", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["When it comes to project planning, knowing if your database or dedicated network share is capable of handling increased data load is essential to avoiding performance failures. While back-end pipeline development, data engineering and infrastructure maintenance isn\u2019t quite as \u2018hot\u2019 as data science, machine learning or analytics nowadays, it\u2019s really the core of a company\u2019s data needs. Without a solid foundation or implementation strategy for handling massive volumes of data from various sources and systems, it will be difficult to perform any transformation on your data.", "This is the type of query that comes up naturally and quite frequently \u2014 are we optimizing our infrastructure?", "Thankfully, instead of having to manually sort through tens of thousands of files from the past three years, we can get Python to do the heavy lifting. When faced with the question of how has our application data needs to be changed over time, I created a handy script to aggregate the data volume by month. Once that\u2019s done, it\u2019s easy to plot the trend over time.", "In the use case here, what I wanted to know was how the month-to-month volume increased for each application on a common Windows network-attached share. Since many services used the same location, it was important to segregate the reports by application first and then secondly by folder location. The best part of this script is that it\u2019s reusable and can be easily configured for any other application or network location since the function is generic.", "Determine the data volume of files on a Windows location on a month-to-month basis", "Parse the timestamp and size of each file then aggregate the total data volume by month", "Step 1: Load the required libraries \u2014 pandas, datetime, os, os.path, time", "Step 2: Name the output file (where you want to save the report)", "Step 3: Create a function to return the total volume for the provided network location in one-month intervals", "Optionally, you can choose to add an additional column for size in MB or GB since the default value returned by Python is in bytes.", "Step 4: Update the script to include all paths and call the above-mentioned getFileSummaryByMonth function", "Step 5: View your results after executing the script \u2014 each folder will be saved as a different tab in the output Excel spreadsheet. Depending on your needs, you can choose to update the script to display the results accordingly.", "To visualize the growth, you can get creative with Tableau depending on your end-goal. Mine was to observe the volume growth over the past three years on monthly intervals. If you know the expected file size, you can accommodate that volume of your spreadsheet accordingly and plot again to predict the overall storage needed.", "Hope this Python script helps you on your data science and data engineering journey!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Always learning / Making sense of the world through analytics / Technology, AI, journalism, data science / https://www.linkedin.com/in/vajiha-sipra-83842224/"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.c